38 @section Types_of_Numbers
39 
40 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_types_of_numbers
41 
42  - NATURAL/CARDINAL NUMBER (ℕ): Counting numbers {0, 1, 2, 3, …}, are called natural numbers. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number)
43  - INTEGER (ℤ): A number that can be written without a fractional component. For example, 17, 3, 0, and -1024 are integers, while 9.73, 5 1⁄2, and √2 are not integers. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer)
44  - RATIONAL NUMBER (ℚ): Any number that can be expressed as the quotient or fraction p/q of two integers, p and q, with the denominator, q, not equal to zero. Since q may be equal to 1, every integer is a rational number. The decimal expansion of a rational number always either terminates after a finite number of digits or begins to repeat the same finite sequence of digits over and over. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number)
45  - TRANSCENDENTAL NUMBER: A real or complex number that is not algebraic; that is, it is not a root of a non-zero polynomial equation with rational coefficients. The best-known transcendental numbers are π and e. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transcendental_number)
46  - REAL NUMBER (ℝ): A value that represents a quantity along a continuous line. The real numbers include all the rational numbers, such as the integer -5 and the fraction 4/3, all the irrational numbers, such as √2 (1.41421356…) and all transcendental numbers, such as π (3.14159265…). (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number)
47  - IRRATIONAL NUMBER (𝕀): Any real number that cannot be expressed as a ratio of integers. Irrational numbers cannot be represented as terminating or repeating decimals. As a consequence of Cantor's proof that the real numbers are uncountable and the rationals countable, almost all real numbers are irrational. Irrational numbers include √2, π, e, and φ. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_number)
48  - IMAGINARY NUMBER: A complex number that can be written as a real number multiplied by the imaginary unit 𝕚. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imaginary_number)
49  - COMPLEX NUMBER (ℂ): A number that can be expressed in the form a + b𝕚, where a and b are real numbers and 𝕚 is the imaginary unit, that satisfies the equation 𝕚^2=-1. In this expression, a is the real part and b is the imaginary part of the complex number. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number)
50  - TESSARINE OR BICOMPLEX-NUMBER: A hypercomplex number in a commutative, associative algebra over real numbers with two imaginary units (designated i and k). (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicomplex_number)
51  - HYPERCOMPLEX NUMBER: An element of a unital algebra over the field of real numbers. Hypercomplex numbers include quaternions, octonions, sedenions, tessarines, coquaternions, and biquaternions. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypercomplex_number)
52  - QUATERNION (ℍ): A number system that extends the complex numbers and applied to mechanics in three-dimensional space. A feature of quaternions is that multiplication of two quaternions is noncommutative. Hamilton defined a quaternion as the quotient of two directed lines in a three-dimensional space or equivalently as the quotient of two vectors. Quaternions form a four-dimensional associative normed division algebra over the real numbers, and therefore also a domain. In fact, the quaternions were the first noncommutative division algebra to be discovered. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion)
53  - SPLIT-QUATERNION OR COQUATERNION: Elements of a 4-dimensional associative algebra. Unlike the quaternion algebra, the split-quaternions contain zero divisors, nilpotent elements, and nontrivial idempotents. As a mathematical structure, they form an algebra over the real numbers, which is isomorphic to the algebra of 2 × 2 real matrices. A coquaternion equals `w + xi + yj + zk`. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Split-quaternion)
54  - BIQUATERNION: Are the numbers w + x i + y j + z k, where w, x, y, and z are complex numbers and the elements of {1, i, j, k} multiply as in the quaternion group. As there are three types of complex numbers, so there are three types of biquaternions (Ordinary Biquaternions, Split-biquaternions, and Dual quaternions). (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biquaternion)
55  - OCTONION (𝕆): Normed division algebra over the real numbers. Octonions have eight dimensions; twice the number of dimensions of the quaternions. They are noncommutative and nonassociative, but satisfy a weaker form of associativity. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Octonion)
56  - SEDENION (𝕊): 16-dimensional noncommutative and nonassociative numbers over the reals and obtained by applying the Cayley–Dickson construction to the octonions. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sedenion)
57 */

204 /** Return logp1 for the given number */
205 double log_plus1(const double num) {
206  if (fabs(num) < (DBL_EPSILON / 2.0)) { return num; }
207  else if ((-0.5 <= num) && (num <= 1.0)) {
208  register double x = (1.0 + num);
209  return ((log(x)) - (((x - 1.0) - num) / x));
210  } else { return (log((1.0 + num))); } // NaNs and infinities
211 }

234 /** log function that fixes odd behaviors on some platforms */
235 double LOG(const double num) {
236  if (isfinite(num)) {
237  if (num > 0.0) { return log(num); }
238  errno = EDOM;
239  if (num == 0.0) { return -HUGE_VAL; } // log(0) = -inf
240  else { return NAN; } // log(-ve) = nan
241  }
242  else if (isnan(num)) { return num; } // log(nan) = nan
243  else if (num > 0.0) { return num; } // log(inf) = inf
244  else {
245  errno = EDOM;
246  return NAN; // log(-inf) = nan
247  }
248 }

251 /** log2 function that fixes odd behaviors on some platforms */
252 double LOG2(const double num) {
253  if (!(isfinite(num))) {
254  if (isnan(num)) { return num; } // log2(nan) = nan
255  else if (num > 0.0) { return num; } // log2(+inf) = +inf
256  else {
257  errno = EDOM;
258  return NAN; // log2(-inf) = nan, invalid-operation
259  }
260  } else if (num > 0.0) {
261  register double m;
262  int e;
263  m = frexp(num, &e);
264  if (num >= 1.0) { return log(2.0 * m) / log(2.0) + (e - 1); }
265  else { return ((log(m) / log(2.0)) + e); }
266  } else if (num == 0.0) {
267  errno = EDOM;
268  return -HUGE_VAL; // log2(0) = -inf, divide-by-zero
269  } else {
270  errno = EDOM;
271  return NAN; // log2(-inf) = nan, invalid-operation
272  }
273 }

296 /** Return base-e minus 1 for the given number */
297 double exp_minus1(const double num) {
298  if (fabs(num) < 0.7) {
299  register double x;
300  x = exp(num);
301  if (x == 1.0) { return num; }
302  else { return (((x - 1.0) * num) / log(x)); }
303  }
304  return (exp(num) - 1.0);
305 }

355 /** Fast power function (num^exp) */
356 double ipow(double num, const int exp) {
357  register int e = exp;
358  if ((int)e < 0x00) {
359  e = -e;
360  num = (1.0 / num);
361  }
362  register double ret = 1.0;
363  while (1) {
364  if (e & 1) { ret *= num; }
365  if ((e >>= 1) == 0) { break; }
366  num *= num;
367  }
368  return ret;
369 }

669 /** Return the Square-Root of a positive number (Limit: 1000000000000000.0) */
670 double squareroot(const double num) {
671  if (num < (double)0.0) return -1.0;
672  else if (floor(num) == num && num <= (double)81.0) {
673  if (num == (double)0.0) return 0.0;
674  else if (num == (double)1.0) return 1.0;
675  else if (num == (double)4.0) return 2.0;
676  else if (num == (double)9.0) return 3.0;
677  else if (num == (double)16.0) return 4.0;
678  else if (num == (double)25.0) return 5.0;
679  else if (num == (double)36.0) return 6.0;
680  else if (num == (double)49.0) return 7.0;
681  else if (num == (double)64.0) return 8.0;
682  else if (num == (double)81.0) return 9.0;
683  }
684  register double start = (double)0.0; // if num < 1; then 0 < num < sqrt(num); else 0 < sqrt(num) < num
685  register double end = (num < (double)1.0 ? (double)1.0 : num);
686  register double mid, midSqr;
687  while ((end - start) > (double)0.00001) { // Define precision
688  mid = (start + end) * (double)0.5;
689  midSqr = mid * mid;
690  if (midSqr == num) return mid; // Exact sqrt value
691  else if (midSqr < num) start = mid;
692  else end = mid;
693  }
694  return (double)((start + end) * (double)0.5);
695 }

1378 /** Returns the principal value of the arc tangent of y/x, expressed in radians */
1379 double ATAN2(const double y, const double x) {
1380  if (isnan(x) || isnan(y)) { return NAN; }
1381  if (isinf(y)) {
1382  if (isinf(x)) {
1383  if (copysign(1.0, x) == 1.0) { return copysign(0.25 * PI, y); } // atan2(+-inf, +inf) == +-pi/4
1384  else { return copysign(0.75 * PI, y); } // atan2(+-inf, -inf) == +-pi*3/4
1385  }
1386  return copysign(0.5 * PI, y); // atan2(+-inf, x) == +-pi/2 for finite x
1387  }
1388  if (isinf(x) || y == 0.0) {
1389  if (copysign(1.0, x) == 1.0) { return copysign(0.0, y); } // atan2(+-y, +inf) = atan2(+-0, +x) = +-0.0
1390  else { return copysign(PI, y); } // atan2(+-y, -inf) = atan2(+-0., -x) = +-pi
1391  }
1392  return atan2(y, x);
1393 }

1396 /** Return the Pi Sine of the given number; return 0.0 on error */
1397 double sinpi(const double num) {
1398  register double r;
1399  if (!(isfinite(num))) { return 0.0; }
1400  register double x = fmod(fabs(num), 2.0);
1401  register slint n = (slint)lround(2.0 * x);
1402  switch (n) {
1403  case 0:
1404  r = sin(PI * x);
1405  break;
1406  case 1:
1407  r = cos(PI * (x - 0.5));
1408  break;
1409  case 2:
1410  r = sin(PI * (1.0 - x));
1411  break;
1412  case 3:
1413  r = (-cos(PI * (x - 1.5)));
1414  break;
1415  case 4:
1416  r = sin(PI * (x - 2.0));
1417  break;
1418  default: // Should never get here
1419  r = 0.0;
1420  break;
1421  }
1422  return (copysign(1.0, num) * r);
1423 }
